Notes to self:
-success and failure as an artist are irrelevant. What is relevant is that you are learning something through your work. 

-the highest honor is when someone connects with your work.

-don’t rush to the high points of your life. There is just as much beauty and inspiration in the in-between moments. 

-the closest thing isn’t always the best thing. 

-if something isn’t working in the timeline you had hoped for, it’s because something even better is coming later. delays are for a reason.

-in order to receive you have to let go.  Let go, then your cup is open. (Kind of like soup. Sometimes soup goes bad. You have to toss out the bad soup before having room in the pot for new, good soup)🙃

-Daydreaming is really important.

-asking for help can take courage, but you will feel better every time you do so.

busy in a good way 👼🏻
Ceramics drop (pun intended) live now for email subscribers 🖤

Getting in the zone with ceramics is truly something else. My favorite part is that your hands get so dirty that you literally cannot touch your phone. So you’re left in that special spot where it’s just you focusing on what is in front of you, and thinking about the functionality of an object. Working with clay is one of the few places where you are safe from the doom-scroll ◡̈ 

Anyway, the pieces in these images are all available in my latest drop on my website! A few have been sold but there are still a few gorgeous pieces available. I have been loving seeing which pieces everyone connects with!

And to anyone who has already purchased something, thank you SO much for your support! It truly means the world <3

It’s always weird editing a full day’s work into 30 seconds or less. I wanted to share my drawing process because it is something I get asked about a lot. The truth is the every time I work on something it feels different. It always requires refining my parameters.

It always starts with a lot of observation. I look at everything through the lens of “how can this be used for mark making”. Watching the world around me as discreetly as possible, and finding points of connection. The more you do this, the more they appear.  Connecting the dots is maybe the most magical part of the process.

Then I gather notes, sketches, forgotten trains of thought, and look through the underlines in half-read books. Sometimes I overhear a conversation and it gives me the missing piece I was looking for. 

Finally, I sit down to make something of all this. I know it’s time to start when when something jumps out at me, that’s my clue to put pen to paper. This is when I make thumbnails, and “figure it all out”, but when it’s time to move to the final piece I get a bit scared and stare at the blank page. 

I wonder if I should even start at all. 

I go back and forth between the page and my sketches, I continue to alter my work, always wondering if I’ve made the right move or if I should start over. There are only a few moments where I feel things are going right, but finally, something starts to emerge, and I almost don’t remember how it all happened. 

.
